0430\u0442\u0442\u043e \u00ab\u0410\u043a\u0442\u0451\u0440\u044b \u0444\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0443\u0437\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0438\u00bb \u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0432 \u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435 \u0445\u0443\u0434\u043e\u0436\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 [Watteau's painting ''Actors of the Com\u00e9die-Fran\u00e7aise'' and the matter of portrait in the artist's work]|editor-last=Izergina|editor-first=A. N.|editor2-last=Nikulin|editor2-first=N. N.|editor2-link=Nikolai Nikulin (art historian)|title=\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0435\u0432\u0440\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0441\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e|trans-title=Western European Art|location=Leningrad|language=ru|publisher=Aurora|pages=145\u2013157|ref=harv|oclc=837241769}}\n* {{cite book|last=Nemilova|first=I. S.|title=\u0424\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0443\u0437\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0436\u0438\u0432\u043e\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c XVIII \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0430 \u0432 \u042d\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0436\u0435 (La peinture fran\u00e7aise du XVIIIe si\u00e8cle, Mus\u00e9e de L\u2019Ermitage: catalogue raisonn\u00e9)|trans-title=French Painting of the 18th centrty in the Hermitage Museum: Scientific Catalogue|location=Leningrad|publisher=Iskusstvo|pages=130\u2013134|year=1982|ref=harv|oclc=63466759}}\n* {{cite book|last=Nemilova|first=I. S.|title=\u0424\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0443\u0437\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0436\u0438\u0432\u043e\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c XVIII \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0430|trans-title=French Painting of the 18th Century|series=\u0413\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u042d\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0436. \u0421\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0436\u0438\u0432\u043e\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438|language=ru|year=1985|location=Moscow|publisher=Izobrazitel'noe iskusstvo|pages=242\u2013243|oclc=878889718}}\n* {{cite book|last=Phillips|first=Claude|author-link=Claude Phillips|title=Antoine Watteau|url=https://archive.org/details/antoinewatteau00phil|pages=[https://archive.org/details/antoinewatteau00phil/page/70 70], 72|year=1895|publisher=Seeley and co. Limited|via=the Internet Archive}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Sch\u00e9fer|first=Gaston|title=Les Portraits dans l\u2019oeuvre de Watteau|language=fr|journal=Gazette des Beaux-Arts|date=September 1896|issue=471|pages=177\u2013189|ref=harv|url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k2031418/f202.image|via=Gallica}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Great French Painting in the Hermitage|last=Sterling|first=Charles|author-link=Charles Sterling|others=Translated from French by Christopher Ligota|publisher=Harry N. Abrams|year=1958|location=New York|oclc=598217|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Stuffmann|first=Margret|date=July\u2013September 1968|title=Les tableaux de la collection de Pierre Crozat : historique et destin\u00e9e d'un ensemble c\u00e9l\u00e8bre \u00e9tablis en partant d'un inventaire apr\u00e8s d\u00e9c\u00e8s in\u00e9dit 30 mai 1740|language=fr|journal=Gazette des Beaux-Arts|volume=72|pages=11\u2013144|ref=harv|oclc=888303109}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=Zolotov|editor-first=Y. K.|title=\u0410\u043d\u0442\u0443\u0430\u043d \u0412\u0430\u0442\u0442\u043e (\u0430\u043b\u044c\u0431\u043e\u043c \u0440\u0435\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0443\u043a\u0446\u0438\u0439)|trans-title=Antoine Watteau: a reproductions album|language=ru|year=1973|ref=harv|location=Leningrad|publisher=Aurora|pages=138\u2013140|oclc=46947007}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite web|url=http://watteau-abecedario.org/Coquettes_qui_pour_voir.htm|title=Coquettes qui pour voir|last=Eidelberg|first=Martin|author-link=Martin Eidelberg|date=January 2019|work=A Watteau Abecedario|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403191650/http://watteau-abecedario.org/Coquettes_qui_pour_voir.htm|archive-date=April 3, 2019|accessdate=April 11, 2019|ref=harv}}\n* [http://www.hermitagemuseum.org/wps/portal/hermitage/digital-collection/01.%20paintings/37439?lng=en ''Actors of the Com\u00e9die-Fran\u00e7aise''] at the Hermitage's official website\n\n{{Jean-Antoine Watteau}}\n\n[[Category:Oil paintings]]\n[[Category:Panel painting]]\n[[Category:1710s paintings]]\n[[Category:Paintings by Antoine Watteau]]\n[[Category:Paintings of the Hermitage Museum]]\n[[Category:Paintings of children]]\n[[Category:Portraits of actors|Comedie-Francaise]]\n[[Category:18th-century portraits]]\n[[Category:Group portraits]]\n[[Category:Crozat collection]]\n", "name_user": "Gleb95", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFurther reading", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Actors_of_the_Com%C3%A9die-Fran%C3%A7aise"}
{"title_page": "Gender Equality Bureau", "text_new": "{{Politics of Japan}}\nThe {{Nihongo|'''Gender Equality Bureau'''|\u7537\u5973\u5171\u540c\u53c2\u753b\u5c40|Danjo Ky\u014dd\u014d Sankakukyoku}} was established in 2001 as a division of the Japanese [[Cabinet Office (Japan)|Cabinet Office]] tasked with planning and coordinating the policies of the [[Japanese Government]] pertaining to [[gender equality]].<ref name=japan>{{cite news |title=Japan |publisher=HumanTrafficking.org}}<!--|accessdate=April 12, 2012--></ref> The Gender Equality Bureau conducts research on topics concerning issues of [[gender]]\u2014compiling findings into an annual report called the \"White Paper\".<ref name=japan />\n\n==History==\nIn 1994, the Headquarters for the Promotion of Gender Equality was created within the [[Cabinet of Japan]].<ref name=Progress>{{cite web|title=Progress of the Government for Realizing a Gender-equal Society |url=http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/about_danjo/toward/progress/index.html |publisher=Gender Equality Bureau |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> With the 1999 implementation of the Basic Law for a Gender-Equal Society, both the Office for Gender Equality and the Council for Gender Equality were established by the Japanese Cabinet.<ref name=Progress /> During the governmental reforms effected January 6, 2001, the Gender Equality Bureau was established under the newly formulated [[Cabinet Office]].<ref name=Progress />\n\nCoupled with the Gender Equality Council, the Bureau is tasked with devising and coordinating plans regarding issues of gender equality in addition to executing plans that fall outside of the jurisdiction of any other ministry.<ref name=Progress /> When first founded, the Gender Equality Bureau was composed of 50 people with an equal balance between male and female members.<ref name=penketh />\n\n==Reasons for creation of the Bureau==\nFormulated partially as a result from outside pressure by [[Feminism in Japan|Japanese feminists]],<ref>{{cite journal|last=Zerbe Enns|first=Carolyn|title=On the rich tapestry of Japanese feminisms|journal=[[Feminism & Psychology]]|date=November 2011|pages=542\u2013546}}</ref> the creation of the Gender Equality Bureau was praised by the [[United Nations]], which cited the need for systemic social changes in Japan.<ref name=matsubara>{{cite news|last=Matsubara|first=Hiroshi|title=U.N. tells Japan to get its act together on gender discrimination|newspaper=The Japan Times|date=August 12, 2003}}</ref> While Japanese women were guaranteed equality in the [[Constitution of Japan|1947 constitution]], many argued that there was a large gap between the ideals of the law and reality.<ref name=struck /> In 1979, 70% of Japanese citizens surveyed agreed with the statement \"the husband should be the [[Breadwinner model|breadwinner]], the wife should [[Housewife|stay at home]]\".<ref name=penketh />\n\nDuring the 1980s\u2014a decade which saw Japan ratify the U.N. Convention on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women in 1985 <ref name=matsubara /> and the proposal of Japan's first National Action Plan for combating gender inequality in 1987<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mofa.go.jp/policy/women/2.html |title=Activities of Japan's National Machinery for Gender Equality |newspaper=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Japan |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref>\u2014one public opinion survey found that 71% of Japanese women favored separate roles for men and women.<ref name=lohr /> Women constituted 1.7% of government management in 1997,<ref name=struck /> and 0.2% of corporate management in 1998.<ref name=fukue /> Facing increasing international pressure from bodies like the United Nations, Japan in the 1990s undertook a variety of efforts that culminated in the creation of the Gender Equality Bureau in 2001.<ref name=Progress />\n\n==Mission statement==\nThe Gender Equality Bureau seeks to promote a \"Gender-Equal Society\", where the human rights of all men and women are equally respected, and both genders have equal opportunity.<ref name=whatis>{{cite web |title=What is a Gender-Equal Society? |url=http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/about_danjo/toward/society/index.html |publisher=Gender Equality Bureau |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> The Bureau states that this goal is predicated on the establishment of a social and policy framework that allows individuals to choose their lifestyle without the limitations of traditional gender views.<ref name=whatis /> Specifically, the Gender Equality Bureau singles out the notion that women are supposed to be [[homemaker]]s and men the breadwinners, calling on all citizens of Japan to \"rethink our prejudiced notions of gender-based roles, so that we may realize a society where men and women can participate together in politics, at the workplace and at home, and lead exciting and fulfilling lives\".<ref name=whatis />\n\n==Measures towards gender-equality==\n\n===Expansion of women's participation in policy and decision-making in all fields of society===\nThe Gender Equality Bureau seeks to increase the amount of power in female hands through the promotion of \"[[positive action]]\",<ref name=expansion>{{cite web |title=Expansion of Women's Participation in Policy and Decision Making Processes in All Fields of Society |url=http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/mge/process/ |publisher=Gender Equality Bureau |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> where legal means are used to amend gender disparities so that both men and women are given equal opportunity to partake in all aspects of society. The current goal the Bureau wishes to achieve is to increase the percentage of women in leadership positions to at least 30% by the year 2020 in a wide range of fields, such as [[academia]] and [[politics]].<ref name=expansion />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Proportion of women for each item !! Subsection of each item !! Currently !! Target (Deadline)\n|-\n| Politics || Election candidates of members of the House of Representatives || 16.7%(2009) || 30% (2020)\n|-\n| National Government || Managers || 2.2%(2009) || 5% (2015)\n|-\n| Local Government || Local public employees for prefectural governments || 21.3%(2008) || 30% (2015)\n|-\n| Private Sector || Section manager or higher in private companies || 6.5%(2009) || 10% (2015)\n|-\n| Education and Research || University professors || 16.7%(2009) || 30% (2020)\n|}\n\n===Work-life balance for men and women===\nThe Gender Equality Bureau defines a [[work-life balance]] as a society in which an individual is not limited by his/her gender in choosing a fulfilling occupation that will accommodate each stage of an individual's life.<ref name=worklife>{{cite web |title=Work-life Balance for Men and Women |url=http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/mge/wlb/ |publisher=Gender Equality |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> Japanese workers on average have a minimum of ten work days for vacation time per year and are given zero paid public holidays, numbers that are far below any other industrialized nation except the United States.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ray|first=Rebecca|author2=John Schmitt|title=No-Vacation Nation|journal=Center for Economic and Policy Research|date=May 2007|pages=1\u201322}}</ref> In order to ensure that Japanese workers are free to lead a healthy and affluent life in a style of their choosing while also maintaining their economic independence, the Gender Equality Bureau in 2007 recommended a variety of policies for both the [[Public sector|public]] and [[private sector]] in order to increase time-off for employees.<ref name=worklife />\n\nThe Bureau has pushed private employers to offer flexible hours that can cater to a variety of lifestyles, such as offering child-care leave for men in order to promote the male's role in child-rearing.<ref name=worklife /> Government, per the Bureau's recommendation, is tasked with providing a policy structure that meets both male and female needs, hiring only companies that practice work-life balance for public contracts, and passing [[legislation]] that signifies the importance of both genders taking an active role in domestic work.<ref name=worklife />\n\n===Stopping violence against women===\n[[File:Gender Equality Bureau flyer providing information about spousal abuse.gif|thumb|right|Gender Equality Bureau flyer providing information about spousal abuse. [http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/mge/violence/index.html Gender.go.jp]]]\n\nIn recognition of the emphasis put on the cessation of [[violence against women]] by the United Nations,<ref name=matsubara /><ref name=elimination>{{cite web |title=Elimination of All Forms of Violence against Women |url=http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/mge/violence/ |publisher=Gender Equality Bureau |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> the Gender Equality Bureau has made many endeavors to eliminate the issue. In 2001, the Bureau formulated the Act on the Prevention of Spousal Violence and the Protection of Victims in an effort to curtail [[domestic abuse]]. The act strives to increase the resources available to victims of spousal abuse while also providing a legal framework for victims to petition for protection against their abusers.<ref name=elimination /> The Gender Equality Bureau also campaigns annually from November 12 through November 25 to raise social awareness of violence against women to coincide with the United Nations' [[International Day for the Elimination of Violence against Women]], in part by providing preventive education materials aimed at youths.<ref name=elimination />\n\n===International cooperation===\nThe Gender Equality Bureau, in seeking to promote gender equality in Japan, has sought guidance from international bodies such as the United Nations, the [[Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation]], and the [[Association of Southeast Asian Nations]].<ref name=International>{{cite web |title=International Cooperation |url=http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/pr_act/pub/pamphlet/women-and-men12/pdf/2-16.pdf |format=pdf |publisher=Gender Equality Bureau |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> In 2010, Japan served as chair of APEC, and held the 15th Women Leaders Network meeting in [[Tokyo]].<ref name=International /> Japan was also one of the initial executives of [[UN Women]], which was formed in January 2011.<ref name=International />\n\nThe Gender Equality Bureau also works with international non-governmental agencies, such as [[Polaris Project]] and [[ECPAT]], to combat issues such as [[human trafficking]] and [[sexual abuse]].<ref name=japan /> Some observers have also noted how international studies on gender inequality, such as those conducted annually by the [[World Economic Forum]], have acted as catalysts for movement on the gender equality front by the Japanese government.<ref name=Tsukino>{{cite news|last=Tsukino|first=Mihoko|title=Gender Equality Long Overdue; U.N. Set to Rap Govt Stance on Women's Rights, Marriage Law, Education|newspaper=The Daily Yomiuri|date=July 30, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n\n===The White Paper===\nThe White Paper is an annual report published by the Gender Equality Bureau that contains both research and policy suggestions for issues of gender inequality. The main object of study for each White Paper remains largely consistent with the measures for gender equality established by the 1999 Basic Laws for a Gender-equal Society, although each new report attempts to address obstacles to the accomplishment of these measures. \nThe 2010 White Paper\u2014the latest year available online\u2014focused on the [[education]] of [[Women in Japan|Japanese women]], calling for their increased education of the variety of career opportunities available to them <ref name=active>{{cite journal|last=Gender Equality Bureau|title=The Active Participation of Women and Revitalization of Economy and Society|journal=White Paper on Gender Equality|year=2010|pages=1\u201314}}</ref> in an attempt to avoid the closing of the next generation of Japanese women's minds due to [[stereotype]]d perception of gender roles in society. The 2010 White Paper also pushes for combating the popular perception of gender equality being only concerned with women, stating that a gender-equal society would benefit both \"the male worker and the housewife\".<ref name=active />\n\n===Other publications===\n\n====\"Stop the Violence\" (2008)====\nThe Gender Equality Bureau publishes a variety of research and pamphlets each year. In 2008, a pamphlet called \"Stop the Violence\" was published, containing information for victims of [[spousal abuse]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Gender Equality Bureau|title=Stop the Violence|url= http://www.gender.go.jp/e-vaw/book/images/pdf/stoptheviolence.pdf |year=2008|publisher=Japanese Cabinet Office|pages=1\u201316}}</ref>\n\n====\"Men and Women of Japan\" (2011)====\nSince 1996, the Gender Equality Bureau published a pamphlet detailing the current status of men and women in contemporary Japan that is presently called ''Women in Men in Japan''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Women in Men in Japan |url=http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/category/pub/pamphlet/women-and-men11/pdf/0.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419221659/http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/category/pub/pamphlet/women-and-men11/pdf/0.pdf |archivedate=April 19, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n====\"Disaster Prevention and Reconstruction from the Perspective of Gender Equality\" (2012)====\nIn the wake of the [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami|Great East Japan earthquake]] on March 11, 2011, the Gender Equality Bureau published a pamphlet for aid-workers on how to properly respond to disasters areas from a gender standpoint.<ref>{{Citation|title=Disaster Prevention and Reconstruction from the Perspective of Gender Equality |url=http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/category/pub/pdf/reconstruction.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419175216/http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/category/pub/pdf/reconstruction.pdf |archivedate=2012-04-19 }}</ref>\n\n==Criticisms==\n\n===Representation of women in public and private sectors===\nDespite the Gender Equality Bureau's efforts to increase representation of women in the public and private sector, some point out that Japan continues to lag far behind other industrialized nations in gender equality.<ref name=penketh>{{cite journal|last=Penketh|first=Anne|title=Japan's Concrete Ceiling: 'Glass Ceiling' Hardly Does Justice to the Sexism Rife in Japanese Business Life|journal=The Independent|date=May 7, 2008|pages=34}}</ref> According to the World Economic Forum, in 2011 Japan was ranked 100th out of 135 countries with regards to \"Economic Participation and Opportunity\", and 80th out of 135 for educational attainment for women.<ref name=hausmann>{{cite journal|last=Hausmann|first=Ricardo |display-authors=etal |title=Global Gender Gap Report 2011|journal=World Economic Forum|year=2011|pages=134\u2013135}}</ref> For female political empowerment, Japan ranked 101st, with an equality score of 0.072, with 1.00 representing total equality.<ref name=hausmann /> To explain this lack of traction, some point to Japan's manifestation of a \"[[glass ceiling]]\" that limits the advancement of women in the workplace,<ref name=penketh /><ref name=fukue>{{cite news |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2009/11/11/business/japanese-women-still-hitting-a-glass-and-bamboo-ceiling-in-the-boardroom/#.UjC5K8ZON8E |last=Fukue |first=Natsuko |title=Japanese women still hitting a glass and bamboo ceiling in the boardroom |newspaper=The Japan Times |date=November 11, 2009 |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=High-Profile Women Tackle Gender Imbalance|newspaper=The Nikkei Weekly (Japan)|date=May 14, 2001}}<!--|accessdate=April 12, 2012--></ref> and a culture that sees women workers as subservient employees who are expected to quit once married.<ref name=struck>{{cite news|last=Struck|first=Doug|title=Breaking the Bamboo Ceiling: Japanese Women Struggling Against Career, Salary Limits|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=August 10, 1999}}</ref> From 1998 to 2009, the percentage of female corporate directors increased from 0.2% to 1.4%, an improvement one Japanese female chairwoman called \"pathetically low\".<ref name=fukue />\n\n===Work-life balance===\nSociologist Yuko Kawanishi, in an interview, said that Japanese [[corporate culture]] has blocked the goal of a work-life balance: \"The men became slaves to the company which became like a family. People got sucked into the system and women had to take care of the home, in a kind of division of labour\".<ref name=penketh /> Others argue that the demanding hours expected of employees in general force women out of the workplace. In 2006\u2014according to one study\u2014almost half of all Japanese women resigned from their jobs once they became pregnant with their first child,<ref name=aono>{{cite journal|last=Aono|first=Atsuko|author2=Keiko Kashiwagi|title=Myth or fact: Conception and realities of Japanese women/mothers|journal=Feminism & Psychology|date=November 2011|pages=516\u2013520}}</ref> and of these women, less than 30% would go on to continue full-time work after [[childbirth]].<ref name=aono /> Critics say that this gendered split of the workforce only perpetuates the notion that women are meant to be homemakers and men the breadwinners.<ref name=fukue /><ref name=ijm>{{cite web |title=Spotlight: The Office to Monitor and Combat Trafficking in Persons |url=http://www.ijm.org/node/194 |publisher=International Justice Mission |url-status=dead |accessdate=September 11, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130914041551/http://www.ijm.org/node/194 |archivedate=September 14, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Violence against women===\nIn response to a 2004 Trafficking in Persons Report by the [[U.S. State Department]] that put international pressure on Japan to increase actions against human trafficking, the Japanese Government in 2009 adopted the Action Plan to Combat Trafficking in Persons. This act provides the [[Japanese government]] with powers to apply [[criminal law]] to human traffickers, and allow government bodies like the Gender Equality Bureau to collaborate with foreign countries and NGOs to protect victims.<ref name=elimination /> The 2011 Trafficking in Persons Report states that the measures undertaken by the Japanese government are \"modest, but overall inadequate\" efforts to combat human trafficking.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Office to Monitor and Combat Trafficking in Persons|title=Trafficking in Persons Report|journal=State Department of the United States|date=June 2011}}</ref>\n\n===International cooperation===\n[[File:Gender Equality Bureau of Japanese Cabinet's poster about human trafficking.gif|thumb|right|Gender Equality Bureau poster against human trafficking. [http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/mge/violence/index.html gender.go.jp]]]\nThe [[United Nations]] has been critical of Japan's failure to annually report the country's progress on gender equality issues,<ref name=matsubara /> and for being slow to implement policies recommended by the U.N. Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination against All Women.<ref name=Tsukino /> Additionally, international studies that focus on gender equality have shown little significant statistical progress for women in Japan.<ref name=hausmann />\n\nSome sects of Japanese society have also been vocal about their opposition to some components of [[gender equality]], in the past complaining that discussions of [[sexual discrimination]] are nothing more than an effort to apply foreign values to Japanese society.<ref name=lohr>{{cite news|last=Lohr|first=Steve|title=Japan's Mistrust of the Feminine Mystique|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 8, 1984}}</ref> \nIn attempting to explain similar criticisms manifest in other countries, some academics have argued that global structures of gender often butt heads with more culture-specific concepts, resulting in tension between the imposed and traditional gender and/or [[sexual norms]].<ref name=Michal>{{cite journal|last=Frenkel|first=Michal|title=Reprogramming Femininity? The Construction of Gender Identities in the Israeli Hi-Tech Industry between Global and Local Gender Orders|journal=Work & Organization|date=July 2008|volume=15|series=4|pages=352\u2013374|doi=10.1111/j.1468-0432.2008.00398.x}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Davids|first=Tine|author2=Francien Van Driel|title=The Unhappy Marriage between Gender and Globalization|journal=Third World Quarterly|date=July 2009|volume=30|issue=5|pages=905\u2013920|doi=10.1080/01436590902959107}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Altman|first=Dennis|title=Rupture or Continuity? The Internalization of Gay Indentities|journal=Social Text|year=1996|volume=48|pages=77\u201394|doi=10.2307/466787}}</ref>\n\nAccording to one study, this tension in Japan is likely to lessen over successive generations, as holders of traditional views tend to belong to an older cohort of the population.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ui|first=Miyoko|author2=Yutaka Matsui|title=Japanese Adults' Sex Role Attitudes and Judgment Criteria Concerning Gender Equality: The Diversity of Gender Egalitarianism|journal=Sex Roles|date=March 2008|pages=412\u2013422|doi=10.1007/s11199-007-9346-6|volume=58 }}</ref> Others argue that the tension between global and local concepts of gender will eventually resolve in the establishment of a third system that will be a unique conglomeration of traditional and global [[gender norms]] for a particular region.<ref name=Michal />\n\n===Global gender gap===\nJapan\u2019s global ranking for female equality had risen four places from 105th in 2013 to 101st in 2015, before plummeting to an all-time low of 111th in 2016, according to the annual Global Gender Gap Report.\n<ref>http://reports.weforum.org/global-gender-gap-report-2016/rankings/</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Overview of gender inequality in Japan]]\n* [[Family policy in Japan]]\n* [[Women in Japan]]\n* [[Feminism in Japan]]\n* [[Kyaria\u016bman]], career woman\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/index.html}}\n\n[[Category:Women in Japan]]\n[[Category:Women's rights in Japan]]\n[[Category:Gender equality ministries]]\n[[Category:Government agencies of Japan]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 2001]]\n", "text_old": "{{Politics of Japan}}\nThe {{Nihongo|'''Gender Equality Bureau'''|\u7537\u5973\u5171\u540c\u53c2\u753b\u5c40|Danjo Ky\u014dd\u014d Sankakukyoku}} was established in 2001 as a division of the Japanese [[Cabinet Office (Japan)|Cabinet Office]] tasked with planning and coordinating the policies of the [[Japanese Government]] pertaining to [[gender equality]].<ref name=japan>{{cite news |title=Japan |publisher=HumanTrafficking.org}}<!--|accessdate=April 12, 2012--></ref> The Gender Equality Bureau conducts research on topics concerning issues of [[gender]]\u2014compiling findings into an annual report called the \"White Paper\".<ref name=japan />\n\n==History==\nIn 1994, the Headquarters for the Promotion of Gender Equality was created within the [[Cabinet of Japan]].<ref name=Progress>{{cite web|title=Progress of the Government for Realizing a Gender-equal Society |url=http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/about_danjo/toward/progress/index.html |publisher=Gender Equality Bureau |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> With the 1999 implementation of the Basic Law for a Gender-Equal Society, both the Office for Gender Equality and the Council for Gender Equality were established by the Japanese Cabinet.<ref name=Progress /> During the governmental reforms effected January 6, 2001, the Gender Equality Bureau was established under the newly formulated [[Cabinet Office]].<ref name=Progress />\n\nCoupled with the Gender Equality Council, the Bureau is tasked with devising and coordinating plans regarding issues of gender equality in addition to executing plans that fall outside of the jurisdiction of any other ministry.<ref name=Progress /> When first founded, the Gender Equality Bureau was composed of 50 people with an equal balance between male and female members.<ref name=penketh />\n\n==Reasons for creation of the Bureau==\nFormulated partially as a result from outside pressure by [[Feminism in Japan|Japanese feminists]],<ref>{{cite journal|last=Zerbe Enns|first=Carolyn|title=On the rich tapestry of Japanese feminisms|journal=[[Feminism & Psychology]]|date=November 2011|pages=542\u2013546}}</ref> the creation of the Gender Equality Bureau was praised by the [[United Nations]], which cited the need for systemic social changes in Japan.<ref name=matsubara>{{cite news|last=Matsubara|first=Hiroshi|title=U.N. tells Japan to get its act together on gender discrimination|newspaper=The Japan Times|date=August 12, 2003}}</ref> While Japanese women were guaranteed equality in the [[Constitution of Japan|1947 constitution]], many argued that there was a large gap between the ideals of the law and reality.<ref name=struck /> In 1979, 70% of Japanese citizens surveyed agreed with the statement \"the husband should be the [[Breadwinner model|breadwinner]], the wife should [[Housewife|stay at home]]\".<ref name=penketh />\n\nDuring the 1980s\u2014a decade which saw Japan ratify the U.N. Convention on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women in 1985 <ref name=matsubara /> and the proposal of Japan's first National Action Plan for combating gender inequality in 1987<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mofa.go.jp/policy/women/2.html |title=Activities of Japan's National Machinery for Gender Equality |newspaper=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Japan |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref>\u2014one public opinion survey found that 71% of Japanese women favored separate roles for men and women.<ref name=lohr /> Women constituted 1.7% of government management in 1997,<ref name=struck /> and 0.2% of corporate management in 1998.<ref name=fukue /> Facing increasing international pressure from bodies like the United Nations, Japan in the 1990s undertook a variety of efforts that culminated in the creation of the Gender Equality Bureau in 2001.<ref name=Progress />\n\n==Mission statement==\nThe Gender Equality Bureau seeks to promote a \"Gender-Equal Society\", where the human rights of all men and women are equally respected, and both genders have equal opportunity.<ref name=whatis>{{cite web |title=What is a Gender-Equal Society? |url=http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/about_danjo/toward/society/index.html |publisher=Gender Equality Bureau |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> The Bureau states that this goal is predicated on the establishment of a social and policy framework that allows individuals to choose their lifestyle without the limitations of traditional gender views.<ref name=whatis /> Specifically, the Gender Equality Bureau singles out the notion that women are supposed to be [[homemaker]]s and men the breadwinners, calling on all citizens of Japan to \"rethink our prejudiced notions of gender-based roles, so that we may realize a society where men and women can participate together in politics, at the workplace and at home, and lead exciting and fulfilling lives\".<ref name=whatis />\n\n==Measures towards gender-equality==\n\n===Expansion of women's participation in policy and decision-making in all fields of society===\nThe Gender Equality Bureau seeks to increase the amount of power in female hands through the promotion of \"[[positive action]]\",<ref name=expansion>{{cite web |title=Expansion of Women's Participation in Policy and Decision Making Processes in All Fields of Society |url=http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/mge/process/ |publisher=Gender Equality Bureau |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> where legal means are used to amend gender disparities so that both men and women are given equal opportunity to partake in all aspects of society. The current goal the Bureau wishes to achieve is to increase the percentage of women in leadership positions to at least 30% by the year 2020 in a wide range of fields, such as [[academia]] and [[politics]].<ref name=expansion />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Proportion of women for each item !! Subsection of each item !! Currently !! Target (Deadline)\n|-\n| Politics || Election candidates of members of the House of Representatives || 16.7%(2009) || 30% (2020)\n|-\n| National Government || Managers || 2.2%(2009) || 5% (2015)\n|-\n| Local Government || Local public employees for prefectural governments || 21.3%(2008) || 30% (2015)\n|-\n| Private Sector || Section manager or higher in private companies || 6.5%(2009) || 10% (2015)\n|-\n| Education and Research || University professors || 16.7%(2009) || 30% (2020)\n|}\n\n===Work-life balance for men and women===\nThe Gender Equality Bureau defines a [[work-life balance]] as a society in which an individual is not limited by his/her gender in choosing a fulfilling occupation that will accommodate each stage of an individual's life.<ref name=worklife>{{cite web |title=Work-life Balance for Men and Women |url=http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/mge/wlb/ |publisher=Gender Equality |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> Japanese workers on average have a minimum of ten work days for vacation time per year and are given zero paid public holidays, numbers that are far below any other industrialized nation except the United States.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ray|first=Rebecca|author2=John Schmitt|title=No-Vacation Nation|journal=Center for Economic and Policy Research|date=May 2007|pages=1\u201322}}</ref> In order to ensure that Japanese workers are free to lead a healthy and affluent life in a style of their choosing while also maintaining their economic independence, the Gender Equality Bureau in 2007 recommended a variety of policies for both the [[Public sector|public]] and [[private sector]] in order to increase time-off for employees.<ref name=worklife />\n\nThe Bureau has pushed private employers to offer flexible hours that can cater to a variety of lifestyles, such as offering child-care leave for men in order to promote the male's role in child-rearing.<ref name=worklife /> Government, per the Bureau's recommendation, is tasked with providing a policy structure that meets both male and female needs, hiring only companies that practice work-life balance for public contracts, and passing [[legislation]] that signifies the importance of both genders taking an active role in domestic work.<ref name=worklife />\n\n===Stopping violence against women===\n[[File:Gender Equality Bureau flyer providing information about spousal abuse.gif|thumb|right|Gender Equality Bureau flyer providing information about spousal abuse. [http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/mge/violence/index.html Gender.go.jp]]]\n\nIn recognition of the emphasis put on the cessation of [[violence against women]] by the United Nations,<ref name=matsubara /><ref name=elimination>{{cite web |title=Elimination of All Forms of Violence against Women |url=http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/mge/violence/ |publisher=Gender Equality Bureau |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> the Gender Equality Bureau has made many endeavors to eliminate the issue. In 2001, the Bureau formulated the Act on the Prevention of Spousal Violence and the Protection of Victims in an effort to curtail [[domestic abuse]]. The act strives to increase the resources available to victims of spousal abuse while also providing a legal framework for victims to petition for protection against their abusers.<ref name=elimination /> The Gender Equality Bureau also campaigns annually from November 12 through November 25 to raise social awareness of violence against women to coincide with the United Nations' [[International Day for the Elimination of Violence against Women]], in part by providing preventive education materials aimed at youths.<ref name=elimination />\n\n===International cooperation===\nThe Gender Equality Bureau, in seeking to promote gender equality in Japan, has sought guidance from international bodies such as the United Nations, the [[Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation]], and the [[Association of Southeast Asian Nations]].<ref name=International>{{cite web |title=International Cooperation |url=http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/pr_act/pub/pamphlet/women-and-men12/pdf/2-16.pdf |format=pdf |publisher=Gender Equality Bureau |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> In 2010, Japan served as chair of APEC, and held the 15th Women Leaders Network meeting in [[Tokyo]].<ref name=International /> Japan was also one of the initial executives of [[UN Women]], which was formed in January 2011.<ref name=International />\n\nThe Gender Equality Bureau also works with international non-governmental agencies, such as [[Polaris Project]] and [[ECPAT]], to combat issues such as [[human trafficking]] and [[sexual abuse]].<ref name=japan /> Some observers have also noted how international studies on gender inequality, such as those conducted annually by the [[World Economic Forum]], have acted as catalysts for movement on the gender equality front by the Japanese government.<ref name=Tsukino>{{cite news|last=Tsukino|first=Mihoko|title=Gender Equality Long Overdue; U.N. Set to Rap Govt Stance on Women's Rights, Marriage Law, Education|newspaper=The Daily Yomiuri|date=July 30, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n\n===The White Paper===\nThe White Paper is an annual report published by the Gender Equality Bureau that contains both research and policy suggestions for issues of gender inequality. The main object of study for each White Paper remains largely consistent with the measures for gender equality established by the 1999 Basic Laws for a Gender-equal Society, although each new report attempts to address obstacles to the accomplishment of these measures. \nThe 2010 White Paper\u2014the latest year available online\u2014focused on the [[education]] of [[Women in Japan|Japanese women]], calling for their increased education of the variety of career opportunities available to them <ref name=active>{{cite journal|last=Gender Equality Bureau|title=The Active Participation of Women and Revitalization of Economy and Society|journal=White Paper on Gender Equality|year=2010|pages=1\u201314}}</ref> in an attempt to avoid the closing of the next generation of Japanese women's minds due to [[stereotype]]d perception of gender roles in society. The 2010 White Paper also pushes for combating the popular perception of gender equality being only concerned with women, stating that a gender-equal society would benefit both \"the male worker and the housewife\".<ref name=active />\n\n===Other publications===\n\n====\"Stop the Violence\" (2008)====\nThe Gender Equality Bureau publishes a variety of research and pamphlets each year. In 2008, a pamphlet called \"Stop the Violence\" was published, containing information for victims of [[spousal abuse]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Gender Equality Bureau|title=Stop the Violence|url= http://www.gender.go.jp/e-vaw/book/images/pdf/stoptheviolence.pdf |year=2008|publisher=Japanese Cabinet Office|pages=1\u201316}}</ref>\n\n====\"Men and Women of Japan\" (2011)====\nSince 1996, the Gender Equality Bureau published a pamphlet detailing the current status of men and women in contemporary Japan that is presently called ''Women in Men in Japan''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Women in Men in Japan |url=http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/category/pub/pamphlet/women-and-men11/pdf/0.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419221659/http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/category/pub/pamphlet/women-and-men11/pdf/0.pdf |archivedate=April 19, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n====\"Disaster Prevention and Reconstruction from the Perspective of Gender Equality\" (2012)====\nIn the wake of the [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami|Great East Japan earthquake]] on March 11, 2011, the Gender Equality Bureau published a pamphlet for aid-workers on how to properly respond to disasters areas from a gender standpoint.<ref>{{Citation|title=Disaster Prevention and Reconstruction from the Perspective of Gender Equality |url=http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/category/pub/pdf/reconstruction.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419175216/http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/category/pub/pdf/reconstruction.pdf |archivedate=2012-04-19 }}</ref>\n\n==Criticisms==\n\n===Representation of women in public and private sectors===\nDespite the Gender Equality Bureau's efforts to increase representation of women in the public and private sector, some point out that Japan continues to lag far behind other industrialized nations in gender equality.<ref name=penketh>{{cite journal|last=Penketh|first=Anne|title=Japan's Concrete Ceiling: 'Glass Ceiling' Hardly Does Justice to the Sexism Rife in Japanese Business Life|journal=The Independent|date=May 7, 2008|pages=34}}</ref> According to the World Economic Forum, in 2011 Japan was ranked 100th out of 135 countries with regards to \"Economic Participation and Opportunity\", and 80th out of 135 for educational attainment for women.<ref name=hausmann>{{cite journal|last=Hausmann|first=Ricardo |display-authors=etal |title=Global Gender Gap Report 2011|journal=World Economic Forum|year=2011|pages=134\u2013135}}</ref> For female political empowerment, Japan ranked 101st, with an equality score of 0.072, with 1.00 representing total equality.<ref name=hausmann /> To explain this lack of traction, some point to Japan's manifestation of a \"[[glass ceiling]]\" that limits the advancement of women in the workplace,<ref name=penketh /><ref name=fukue>{{cite news |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2009/11/11/business/japanese-women-still-hitting-a-glass-and-bamboo-ceiling-in-the-boardroom/#.UjC5K8ZON8E |last=Fukue |first=Natsuko |title=Japanese women still hitting a glass and bamboo ceiling in the boardroom |newspaper=The Japan Times |date=November 11, 2009 |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=High-Profile Women Tackle Gender Imbalance|newspaper=The Nikkei Weekly (Japan)|date=May 14, 2001}}<!--|accessdate=April 12, 2012--></ref> and a culture that sees women workers as subservient employees who are expected to quit once married.<ref name=struck>{{cite news|last=Struck|first=Doug|title=Breaking the Bamboo Ceiling: Japanese Women Struggling Against Career, Salary Limits|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=August 10, 1999}}</ref> From 1998 to 2009, the percentage of female corporate directors increased from 0.2% to 1.4%, an improvement one Japanese female chairwoman called \"pathetically low\".<ref name=fukue />\n\n===Work-life balance===\nSociologist Yuko Kawanishi, in an interview, said that Japanese [[corporate culture]] has blocked the goal of a work-life balance: \"The men became slaves to the company which became like a family. People got sucked into the system and women had to take care of the home, in a kind of division of labour\".<ref name=penketh /> Others argue that the demanding hours expected of employees in general force women out of the workplace. In 2006\u2014according to one study\u2014almost half of all Japanese women resigned from their jobs once they became pregnant with their first child,<ref name=aono>{{cite journal|last=Aono|first=Atsuko|author2=Keiko Kashiwagi|title=Myth or fact: Conception and realities of Japanese women/mothers|journal=Feminism & Psychology|date=November 2011|pages=516\u2013520}}</ref> and of these women, less than 30% would go on to continue full-time work after [[childbirth]].<ref name=aono /> Critics say that this gendered split of the workforce only perpetuates the notion that women are meant to be homemakers and men the breadwinners.<ref name=fukue /><ref name=ijm>{{cite web |title=Spotlight: The Office to Monitor and Combat Trafficking in Persons |url=http://www.ijm.org/node/194 |publisher=International Justice Mission |url-status=dead |accessdate=September 11, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130914041551/http://www.ijm.org/node/194 |archivedate=September 14, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Violence against women===\nIn response to a 2004 Trafficking in Persons Report by the [[U.S. State Department]] that put international pressure on Japan to increase actions against human trafficking, the Japanese Government in 2009 adopted the Action Plan to Combat Trafficking in Persons. This act provides the [[Japanese government]] with powers to apply [[criminal law]] to human traffickers, and allow government bodies like the Gender Equality Bureau to collaborate with foreign countries and NGOs to protect victims.<ref name=elimination /> The 2011 Trafficking in Persons Report states that the measures undertaken by the Japanese government are \"modest, but overall inadequate\" efforts to combat human trafficking.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Office to Monitor and Combat Trafficking in Persons|title=Trafficking in Persons Report|journal=State Department of the United States|date=June 2011}}</ref>\n\n===International cooperation===\n[[File:Gender Equality Bureau of Japanese Cabinet's poster about human trafficking.gif|thumb|right|Gender Equality Bureau poster against human trafficking. [http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/mge/violence/index.html gender.go.jp]]]\nThe [[United Nations]] has been critical of Japan's failure to annually report the country's progress on gender equality issues,<ref name=matsubara /> and for being slow to implement policies recommended by the U.N. Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination against All Women.<ref name=Tsukino /> Additionally, international studies that focus on gender equality have shown little significant statistical progress for women in Japan.<ref name=hausmann />\n\nSome sects of Japanese society have also been vocal about their opposition to some components of [[gender equality]], in the past complaining that discussions of [[sexual discrimination]] are nothing more than an effort to apply foreign values to Japanese society.<ref name=lohr>{{cite news|last=Lohr|first=Steve|title=Japan's Mistrust of the Feminine Mystique|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 8, 1984}}</ref> \nIn attempting to explain similar criticisms manifest in other countries, some academics have argued that global structures of gender often butt heads with more culture-specific concepts, resulting in tension between the imposed and traditional gender and/or [[sexual norms]].<ref name=Michal>{{cite journal|last=Frenkel|first=Michal|title=Reprogramming Femininity? The Construction of Gender Identities in the Israeli Hi-Tech Industry between Global and Local Gender Orders|journal=Work & Organization|date=July 2008|volume=15|series=4|pages=352\u2013374|doi=10.1111/j.1468-0432.2008.00398.x}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Davids|first=Tine|author2=Francien Van Driel|title=The Unhappy Marriage between Gender and Globalization|journal=Third World Quarterly|date=July 2009|volume=30|issue=5|pages=905\u2013920|doi=10.1080/01436590902959107}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Altman|first=Dennis|title=Rupture or Continuity? The Internalization of Gay Indentities|journal=Social Text|year=1996|volume=48|pages=77\u201394|doi=10.2307/466787}}</ref>\n\nAccording to one study, this tension in Japan is likely to lessen over successive generations, as holders of traditional views tend to belong to an older cohort of the population.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ui|first=Miyoko|author2=Yutaka Matsui|title=Japanese Adults' Sex Role Attitudes and Judgment Criteria Concerning Gender Equality: The Diversity of Gender Egalitarianism|journal=Sex Roles|date=March 2008|pages=412\u2013422|doi=10.1007/s11199-007-9346-6 }}</ref> Others argue that the tension between global and local concepts of gender will eventually resolve in the establishment of a third system that will be a unique conglomeration of traditional and global [[gender norms]] for a particular region.<ref name=Michal />\n\n===Global gender gap===\nJapan\u2019s global ranking for female equality had risen four places from 105th in 2013 to 101st in 2015, before plummeting to an all-time low of 111th in 2016, according to the annual Global Gender Gap Report.\n<ref>http://reports.weforum.org/global-gender-gap-report-2016/rankings/</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Overview of gender inequality in Japan]]\n* [[Family policy in Japan]]\n* [[Women in Japan]]\n* [[Feminism in Japan]]\n* [[Kyaria\u016bman]], career woman\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.gender.go.jp/english_contents/index.html}}\n\n[[Category:Women in Japan]]\n[[Category:Women's rights in Japan]]\n[[Category:Gender equality ministries]]\n[[Category:Government agencies of Japan]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 2001]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInternational cooperation:Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gender_Equality_Bureau"}
{"title_page": "Monaghan Hospital", "text_new": "{{short description|Hospital in the town of Monaghan, County Monaghan, Ireland}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Monaghan Hospital\n| Org/Group  = [[Health Service Executive]]\n| Image      = Monaghan Hospital, Mullach Glas (geograph 5169848).jpg\n| Caption    = Monaghan Hospital\n| Logo       = <!-- optional -->\n| Location   = [[Monaghan]]\n| Region     = [[County Monaghan]]\n| State      = \n| Country    = [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| HealthCare = [[Health Service Executive|HSE]]\n| Type       = Specialist\n| Speciality = Rehabilitation\n| Emergency  = Yes\n| Affiliation= \n| Beds       =\n| Founded    = 1896\n| Closed     = <!-- optional -->\n| Website    = {{URL|https://www.hse.ie/eng/services/list/3/acutehospitals/hospitals/cavanmonaghan/cavan-monaghan-hospital.html}}\n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n| map_type   = Ireland\n| map_caption= Shown in Ireland\n| coordinates={{coord|54.2502|-6.9744|display=inline,title}}\n|}}\n'''Monaghan General Hospital''' ({{lang-ga|Ospid\u00e9al Mhuineach\u00e1in}}) is a hospital in the town of [[Monaghan]], [[County Monaghan]], [[Republic of Ireland]].\n\n==History and operations==\nThe hospital has its origins in several of the former Monaghan County Jail buildings which were converted for clinical use as Monaghan Infirmary in 1896.<ref name=council>{{cite web|url=https://monaghan.ie/museum/monaghan-hospital/|title=Monaghan Hospital|publisher=Monaghan County Coucil|accessdate=24 May 2019}}</ref> \n\nA purpose-built hospital was officially opened on the site in 1938.<ref name=council/> After the hospital ceased providing acute services in 2009, it began a new role focussing on rehabilitation and \"step-down\" services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2008/1023/109605-health/|title=End of acute services at Monaghan Hospital|date=23 October 2008|publisher=RTE|accessdate=24 May 2019}}</ref> A minor injuries unit remains on the site.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/health/other-hospitals-to-take-on-burden-as-monaghan-loses-acute-services-95979.html|title=Other hospitals to take on burden as Monaghan loses acute services|date=9 July 2009|accessdate=24 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nMonaghan Hospital is managed by one of the Health Service Executive's hospital groups, [[RCSI Hospitals]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imt.ie/news/six-hospital-groups-most-fundamental-reform-in-decades-14-05-2013/|title=Six hospital groups 'most fundamental reform in decades'|date=14 May 2013|publisher=Irish Medical Times|accessdate=27 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals in County Monaghan]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Monaghan (town)]]\n[[Category:Health Service Executive hospitals]]\n[[Category:1896 establishments in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1896]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1938]]\n\n{{Ireland-hospital-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Hospital in the town of Monaghan, County Monaghan, Ireland}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Monaghan Hospital\n| Org/Group  = [[Health Service Executive]]\n| Image      = Monaghan Hospital, Mullach Glas (geograph 5169848).jpg\n| Caption    = Monaghan Hospital\n| Logo       = <!-- optional -->\n| Location   = [[Monaghan]]\n| Region     = [[County Monaghan]]\n| State      = \n| Country    = [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| HealthCare = [[Health Service Executive|HSE]]\n| Type       = Specialist\n| Speciality = Rehabilitation\n| Emergency  = Yes\n| Affiliation= \n| Beds       =\n| Founded    = 1896\n| Closed     = <!-- optional -->\n| Website    = {{URL|https://www.hse.ie/eng/services/list/3/acutehospitals/hospitals/cavanmonaghan/cavan-monaghan-hospital.html}}\n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n| map_type   = Ireland\n| map_caption= Shown in Ireland\n| coordinates={{coord|54.2502|-6.9744|display=inline,title}}\n|}}\n'''Monaghan General Hospital''' ({{lang-ga|Ospid\u00e9al Mhuineach\u00e1in}}) is a hospital in the town of [[Monaghan]], [[County Monaghan]], [[Republic of Ireland]].\n\n==History and operations==\nThe hospital has its origins in several of the former Monaghan County Jail buildings which were converted for clinical use as Monaghan Infirmary in 1896.<ref name=council>{{cite web|url=https://monaghan.ie/museum/monaghan-hospital/|title=Monaghan Hospital|publisher=Monaghan County Coucil|accessdate=24 May 2019}}</ref> A purpose built hospital was officially opened on the site in 1938.<ref name=council/> After the hospital ceased providing acute services in 2009, it began a new role focussing on rehabilitation and step-down services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2008/1023/109605-health/|title=End of acute services at Monaghan Hospital|date=23 October 2008|publisher=RTE|accessdate=24 May 2019}}</ref> A minor injuries unit remains on the site.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/health/other-hospitals-to-take-on-burden-as-monaghan-loses-acute-services-95979.html|title=Other hospitals to take on burden as Monaghan loses acute services|date=9 July 2009|accessdate=24 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nMonaghan Hospital is managed by one of the Health Service Executive's hospital groups, [[RCSI Hospitals]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imt.ie/news/six-hospital-groups-most-fundamental-reform-in-decades-14-05-2013/|title=Six hospital groups 'most fundamental reform in decades'|date=14 May 2013|publisher=Irish Medical Times|accessdate=27 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals in County Monaghan]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Monaghan (town)]]\n[[Category:Health Service Executive hospitals]]\n[[Category:1896 establishments in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1896]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1938]]\n\n{{Ireland-hospital-stub}}\n", "name_user": "SeoR", "label": "safe", "comment": "Punc.; will check refs. for more detail to expand the article.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monaghan_Hospital"}
{"title_page": "Pangasinan", "text_new": "{{about|the province in the Philippines}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Pangasinan\n| official_name           = Province of Pangasinan<ref>({{lang-pag|Luyag na Pangasinan}}; {{lang-tl|Lalawigan ng Pangasinan}}; {{lang-ilo|Probinsia ti Pangasinan}})</ref>\n| settlement_type         = {{PH wikidata|settlement_type}}\n| image_skyline           = File:Pangasinan_Capitol_-_side_view_(Lingayen,_Pangasinan)(2018-02-25).jpg\n| image_caption           = Pangasinan Provincial Capitol in Lingayen\n| image_flag              = {{PH wikidata|image_flag}}\n| flag_size               = 120x80px\n| image_seal              = {{PH wikidata|image_seal}}\n| seal_size               = 120x80px\n| image_map               = {{PH wikidata|image_map}}\n| anthem                  = ''Luyag Ko Tan Yaman''\n| etymology               = ''Pang-asin-an'', lit. ''Place where salt is made''\n| map_caption             = Location in the Philippines\n| coordinates             = {{PH wikidata|coordinates}}\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = {{PH wikidata|country}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Regions of the Philippines|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1       = {{PH wikidata|region}}\n| established_title       = Founded\n| established_date        = April 5, 1580\n| seat_type               = Capital\n| seat                    = {{PH wikidata|seat}}\n| government_type         = {{PH wikidata|government_type}}\n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = [[Governor]]\n| leader_name             = Amado I. Espino III\n| leader_title1           = [[Vice Governor]]\n| leader_name1            = Mark Ronald D. Lambino\n| area_footnotes          = <ref name=nscblist>{{cite web |title=List of Provinces |url=http://www.nscb.gov.ph/activestats/psgc/listprov.asp |work=PSGC Interactive |publisher=National Statistical Coordination Board |accessdate=11 February 2013 |locat